## move-by-ext.ps1
PowerShell script to move (cut) files by extension into organized format folders, featuring duplicate management and logging.
------------------------------
## Key Features

* Recursive scanning of the Root folder.
* Filtering by extensions (e.g., js,css,html) with robust argument normalization.
* Optional filters: minimum/maximum size and modification time range.
* Moving to Target\<extension>\ while preserving original names whenever possible.
* Duplicate management: two strategies — timestamp (default) or increment.
* Detailed CSV log with rows for each file: Timestamp,Source,Destination,Status,Message,SizeBytes,LastWriteTime.
* DryRun mode to simulate operations without modifying any files.
* Console debugging to verify how extensions are being normalized.

------------------------------
## Requirements

* Windows PowerShell (modern version recommended).
* Read/write permissions on the involved folders.
* If working with protected paths, run PowerShell as administrator.

------------------------------
## Usage and Parameters

.\move-by-ext.ps1 -Root "C:\project" -Target "C:\temp" -Extensions "js,css,html" -DryRun


* -Root — folder to scan (default: current folder).
* -Target — target destination folder (mandatory).
* -Extensions — extensions to search for; accepts strings like "js,css" or multiple parameters; the value is automatically normalized.
* -DryRun — simulation mode: no files are moved; actions are recorded in the log with Status=DRY.
* -MinSizeMB — minimum size in MB (optional).
* -MaxSizeMB — maximum size in MB (0 = no limit).
* -ModifiedWithinHours — filters files modified within the last N hours (0 = no filter).
* -RenameStrategy — timestamp (default) or increment to resolve name conflicts.
* -LogFile — path to the CSV log file (default: Target\move-by-ext-log.csv).

------------------------------
## Practical Examples

* Simulation from the current folder:

.\move-by-ext.ps1 -Target "C:\temp" -Extensions "js,css" -DryRun


* Real execution on a specific root:

.\move-by-ext.ps1 -Root "C:\project" -Target "C:\temp" -Extensions "js,css,html"


* Filter by size and date:

.\move-by-ext.ps1 -Root "C:\project" -Target "C:\temp" -Extensions "js,css" -MinSizeMB 0.1 -ModifiedWithinHours 2


* Passing the Extensions parameter multiple times:

.\move-by-ext.ps1 -Target "C:\temp" -Extensions js -Extensions css -DryRun

------------------------------
## Duplicate Management and Logging

* Timestamp strategy — adds a _YYYYMMDD_HHMMSSfff suffix before the extension (e.g., file_20260314_122630123.js). Useful for uniqueness and traceability.
* Increment strategy — adds _1, _2, ... to the same base name. Useful for ordered file series.
* CSV Log — every operation (DRY/OK/ERROR) is recorded with: Timestamp, Source, Destination, Status, Message, SizeBytes, LastWriteTime. The log file is located by default in Target\move-by-ext-log.csv.

------------------------------
## Quick Troubleshooting

* If the Matching files count is 0: verify the -Root value and the extensions using:

Get-ChildItem -Path (Resolve-Path ".").Path -Recurse -File |
Where-Object { @("js","css") -contains $_.Extension.TrimStart('.').ToLower() } |
Select-Object -First 20 FullName


* If the script fails to detect extensions passed as a string, use the "js,css" format or pass -Extensions multiple times. The script normalizes both cases.
* For console encoding issues (accented characters displaying incorrectly), set the encoding with:

chcp 65001
$OutputEncoding = [System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new()


* If some files are in use, Move-Item will fail for those specific files; the log will show Status=ERROR along with the exception message.

------------------------------
## Operational Tips

* Always run in -DryRun first to check the file list and the log.
* For large file trees, scanning may take time; consider running the script on sub-folders or using the MinSizeMB/ModifiedWithinHours filters to reduce the dataset.
* If you need a different duplicate behavior (e.g., controlled overwrite or keeping both with metadata), I can adapt the script for you.

